reality and subjectivity – as well as female body hair, sexuality and violence – She-wolf reveals the varied ways in which the female werewolf is a manifestation of complex cultural anxieties, as well as a site of continued fascination.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPopular culture and literature. 0aWerewolvesxHistory. 4aGothic 2017. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Science Fiction & Fantasy.2bisacsh  aA Ballad of the Were-wolf.  aClemence Housman.  aGinger Snaps.  aHonoré Beaugrand.  aRosamund Marriott Watson.  aSaaremaa.  aThe Werewolf.  aThe Werewolves.  aWerewolf: The Apocalypse.  acultural history.  afemale werewolf.  afemme animale.  afolkloric records.  ahorror cinema.1 aCate, Jay, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCininas, Jazmina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCreed, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrossen, Carys, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHutchings, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMetsvahi, Merili, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPriest, Hannah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPriest, Hannah, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSchulte, Rolf, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aScott, Shannon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilson, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 ade Blécourt, Willem, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2015 eBook-Packagez978311128311140uhttps://doi.org/1